assistant:
You can declare and initialize variables of any type with statements like these:
```
declare integer age = 37;
declare string name = 'John';
declare boolean married = TRUE;
```

Use the function call statement like this:
```
function doSomething();
    // Code here
endfunction;
```

Use a cursor to traverse the rows and access their fields:
```
cursor = database.Open('customers');
while (cursor.NotEnd) do
    name = cursor.Field('name');
    address = cursor.Field('address');
    city = cursor.Field('city');
    province = cursor.Field('province');
    coutn = cursor.Field('count');
    coutn = coutn + 1;
    database.Close();
endwhile;
```

Declare a variable that holds an array of strings like this:
```
var names = new Array(10);
names[0] = 'John';
names[1] = 'Jane';
// etc.
```

Use property references to access attributes like this:
```
person.Name = 'Sally';
person.Address.City = 'New York';
```

Here's how to create and populate an array of strings in Actian 4GL:
```
create array (strings) as list of string;
strings = ['Red', 'Green', 'Blue', 'Yellow'];
add to field(title).value = 'Colors';
```

You can loop through all records in a table like this:
```
for i = 1 to table.Rowcount do
    // Access fields of current record
    field(title).value = record.Field('Title');
    // Do something with the data
endfor;
```

Use the property reference to set values like this:
```
vehicle.Color = 'red';
vehicle.Speed = 60;
```
